 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Rail Ticket Price Prediction using Machine Learning Algorithms**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### OBJECTIVE\n",
    "\n",
    "Travel ticket prices fluctuate frequently based on demand and time. The objective is to predict the demand and prices of train tickets for the upcoming months based on historical data using machine learning algorithms. \n",
    "<br>There are millions of people commuting between several places and at different periods of time. The results of this forecast can be used to analyze and understand the price fluctuations with respect to the route (origin and destination) and time (Date of travel) and several other parameters. This can  can eventually help the commuters plan accordingly in advance and save significant time and money. This can guide users to purchase train tickets in the best period according to their route.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### RESEARCH QUESTION\n",
    "\n",
    "1. To find the most accurate machine learning model applicable to the current dataset for the prediction of train ticket pricing based on the route, period of travel and other parameters. \n",
    "\n",
    "2. To analyze and understand the parameters influencing the price of the tickets.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Description of the dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset contains details regarding the ticket pricing monitoring system of Spanish High Speed Train Service (Renfe AVE). The details of the dataset are as follows: "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**About the dataset** \n",
    "\n",
    "**origin**: The name of the city from where the train starts.\n",
    "<br>**destination**: The name of the city where the train ends, the final stop.\n",
    "<br>**start_date**: The date from when the ticket is valid and the departure time (European Central Time).\n",
    "<br>**end_date**: The date until which the ticket is valid and the arrival time (European Central Time).\n",
    "<br>**train_type**: The type of the train, the service name of the train.\n",
    "<br>**price**: The price of the tickets.\n",
    "<br>**train_class**: The class of the ticket, like economy, business and first class.\n",
    "<br>**fare**: Tells the type of ticket purchased, like adult , promo ticket."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Let us examine each column in detail."
   ]
  },

   "metadata": {},

   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def handle_non_numerical_data(df):\n",
    "    columns = df.columns.values\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for column in columns:\n",
    "        text_digit_vals = {} \n",
    "        def convert_to_int(val):\n",
    "            return text_digit_vals[val]\n",
    "        \n",
    "        if df[column].dtype != np.int64 and df[column].dtype != np.float64:\n",
    "            column_contents = df[column].values.tolist()\n",
    "            unique_elements = set(column_contents)\n",
    "            x=0\n",
    "            for unique in unique_elements:\n",
    "                if unique not in text_digit_vals:\n",
    "                    text_digit_vals[unique] = x\n",
    "                    x = x + 1\n",
    "            \n",
    "            df[column] = list(map(convert_to_int, df[column]))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return df"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df = handle_non_numerical_data(df)"
   ]
  },

    "**TO REMOVE OUTLIERS**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def remove_outlier(df_in, col_name):\n",
    "    q1 = df_in[col_name].quantile(0.25)\n",
    "    q3 = df_in[col_name].quantile(0.75)\n",
    "    iqr = q3-q1\n",
    "    fence_low  = q1-1.5*iqr\n",
    "    fence_high = q3+1.5*iqr\n",
    "    df_out = df_in.loc[(df_in[col_name] > fence_low) & (df_in[col_name] < fence_high)]\n",
    "    return df_out"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df = remove_outlier(df, \"price\")"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def build_evaluate_fn(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):\n",
    "    def evaluate1(model):\n",
    "        train_score = model.score(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "        test_score = model.score(X_test, y_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "        print(\"Train Score:\", train_score)\n",
    "        print(\"Test Score:\", test_score)\n",
    "        print()\n",
    "        \n",
    "        \n",
    "    \n",
    "    return evaluate1\n",
    "\n",
    "evaluate1 = build_evaluate_fn(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Metrics used to validate the model:\n",
    "\n",
    "MEAN ABSOLUTE ERROR (MAE):\n",
    "MAE is the average prediction error, which is the average of the difference between the predicted and actual values in the test data.\n",
    "There is no ideal value for MAE, but lesser the value the better the model fits the data. If the value is 0 it means the model fits the data perfectly.\n",
    "\n",
    "MEAN SQUARED ERROR (MSE):\n",
    "MSE is the average squared difference between the predicted and actual values. In other words, it is the sum of all the data points, of the square of the difference between the predicted and actual values divided by the number of data points.\n",
    "To tell if a model is a good fit or not, the value should as low as possible, if the value is 0, it means it is a perfect fit.\n",
    "\n",
    "ROOT MEAN SQUARE ERROR (RMSE):\n",
    "RMSE is the square root of MSE and is measured in the same units as the target variable.\n",
    "Similar to MSE, the value for RMSE also should be less, near to 0, if it is 0, the model is a perfect fit.\n",
    "\n",
    "R-SQUARED (R2):\n",
    "R2 represents how good the data fits the model. The ideal value of R2 should be 1. The closer the value of R2 to 1, the better is the fit of the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 29,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn import metrics\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score\n",
    "\n",
    "def print_evaluate(true, predicted):  \n",
    "    mae = metrics.mean_absolute_error(true, predicted)\n",
    "    mse = metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted)\n",
    "    rmse = np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted))\n",
    "    r2_square = metrics.r2_score(true, predicted)\n",
    "    print('MAE:', mae)\n",
    "    print('MSE:', mse)\n",
    "    print('RMSE:', rmse)\n",
    "    print('R2 Square', r2_square)\n",
    "    \n",
    "#def evaluate(true, predicted):\n",
    "    #mae = metrics.mean_absolute_error(true, predicted)\n",
    "    #mse = metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted)\n",
    "    #rmse = np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted))\n",
    "    #r2_square = metrics.r2_score(true, predicted)\n",
    "    #return mae, mse, rmse, r2_square"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 1. *__LINEAR REGRESSION__*\n",
    "\n",
    "- Linear regression is based on supervised learning, where the system is trained with the help of input and output patterns to accomplish a task.\n",
    " - Linear regression is used to predict __y__, a dependent variable value based on __x__, an independent variable value. This technique finds a linear relationship between __x__ (input) and __y__ (output).\n",
    " "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Why Linear Regression?\n",
    "\n",
    " - Linear regression is used by many people for prediction / forecasting purposes, so it is an accepted model for doing predictive modelling.\n",
    " - The computational speed is fast as it does not involve any complex calculations.\n",
    " - It works well with large data sets. Since this dataset contains more than 7 million rows, the Linear Regression model is a good fit for this.\n",
    " - To avoid overfitting in this dataset, Linear regression model can be used to regularize it.  \n",
    " - A linear model can be easily updated with new data by using stochastic gradient descent."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

    "### 2. *__RIDGE REGRESSION__*\n",
    "\n",
    "- Ridge regression is used to analyze multiple regression data that suffer from multicollinearity, when independent variables are highly correlated. Multicollinearity is caused when the variance of least squares estimates is very large even though they are not biased, it deviates the predicted value far from the true value.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Why Ridge Regression?\n",
    "\n",
    " - Ridge regression avoids overfitting of the model and hence fits unique values.\n",
    " - Ridge regression reduces standard errors by adding a degree of bias to the regression estimates.\n",
    " - It works very well with multivariate data, even if the number of predictors are more than the number of observations.\n",
    " "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 34,
   "metadata": {},

     "name": "stdout",

     ]

    "### 3. *__RANDOM FOREST REGRESSOR__*\n",
    "\n",
    "  - Random forest is an ensemble method which performs regression with the help of multiple decision trees and a technique called    bagging (Bootstrap aggregation), which involves training each decision tree with different data sample, and sampling is done    with replacement. \n",
    " - Random forest work by training each decision tree and combines multiple decision trees in predicting the output than relying    on a single decision tree. \n",
    " - More the number of trees better the accuracy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Why Random Forest Regressor?\n",
    "\n",
    " - Random forest technique can handle huge amount of data, as it has the ability to work with multiple variables.\n",
    " - They provide a special method to work with missing data, by substituting the missing values with the most repeated value in a    particular node.\n",
    " - This technique can handle variables fast and can be used for complicated tasks.\n",
    " - It is one of the best supervised learning algorithms which gives high accuracy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [

      "RMSE: 7.653638116931682\n",
      "R2 Square 0.9032628879564052\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor\n",
    "\n",

    "rf_reg.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "pred = rf_reg.predict(X_test)\n",

    "print_evaluate(y_test, pred)"

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4. *__GRADIENT BOOSTING REGRESSOR__*\n",
    "\n",
    "- Gradient boosting uses decision trees for prediction, by adding new trees by predicting the errors of the previous tree and      add the value to the previous tree to get the final prediction."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Why Gradient Boosting Regressor?\n",
    "\n",
    "- Provides better accuracy.\n",
    " - Works well with numerical and categorical values, that is , it needs no data pre-processing.\n",
    " - Handles huge amount of data efficiently.\n",
    " - Trains the data fast.\n",
    " - Capable of handling missing data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 38,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "MAE: 6.945992411440372\n",
      "MSE: 95.39402575680714\n",
      "RMSE: 9.766986523836671\n",
      "R2 Square 0.8424644958050387\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "gbr = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=200)\n",
    "gbr.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "pred = gbr.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "print_evaluate(y_test, pred)"
   ]
  },

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 5. *__EXTREME GRADIENT BOOST__* \n",
    "\n",
    " - XGBoost is an implementation of gradient boosted decision trees.\n",
    " - It is mainly designed for speed and performance, which is achieved by pushing the limits of the computation's resources.\n",
    " - The XGBoost algorithm works by iteratively training the trees and by adding new trees to predict the errors of the prior        trees, which are then added to the previous tree to make the final prediction.\n",
    " - It minimizes the loss when adding new trees."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Why Extreme Gradient Boost?\n",
    "\n",
    "- XGBoost is an easy and efficient algorithm providing high speed, accuracy and performance.\n",
    " - It has an in-built L1 (Lasso Regression) and L2 (Ridge Regression) regularization which prevents overfitting of the model.\n",
    " - It has an in-built ability to handle missing values.\n",
    " - It is highly scalable, works parallelly.\n",
    " - Its execution speed is fast.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 41,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import xgboost\n",
    "from xgboost import XGBRegressor\n",
    "xgbr = XGBRegressor(colsample_bytree=0.4,\n",
    "            gamma=0,\n",
    "            learning_rate=0.07,\n",
    "            max_depth=3,\n",
    "            min_child_weight=1.5,\n",
    "            n_estimators=1500,                                                                 \n",
    "            reg_alpha=0.75,\n",
    "            reg_lambda=0.45,\n",
    "            subsample=0.6,\n",
    "            seed=64)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,

    "### 6. *__LIGHT GRADIENT BOOSTING MACHINE__*\n",
    "\n",
    "- LightGBM is a fast and high-performance gradient boosting framework, which uses tree-based learning algorithms.\n",
    "- LightGBM works vertically, that is, it splits the tree leaf-wise and not level-wise like other algorithms."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Why Light Gradient Boosting Machine?\n",
    "\n",
    " - Faster training speed.\n",
    " - Higher efficiency.\n",
    " - Memory usage is low.\n",
    " - It gives better accuracy.\n",
    " - Supports parallel learning.\n",
    " - Can handle large data."
   ]
  },
  {

   "source": [
    "import datetime\n",
    "df2 = res\n",
    "for column in ['start_date', 'end_date']:\n",
    "    date_column = pd.to_datetime(df2[column])\n",
    "    df2[column + '_dayname'] = date_column.dt.day_name(locale = \"English\")\n",
    "    df2[column + '_day'] = date_column.dt.day\n",
    "    df2[column + '_month'] = date_column.dt.month_name(locale = \"English\")\n",
    "    df2[column + '_year'] = date_column.dt.year\n",
    "del df2[column]"
   ]

    "The above graph shows the distribution of prices between actual and predicted (Random Forest Regression) prices.\n",
    "<br>As we had seen earlier, *RANDOM FOREST REGRESSION* is the nearest to the actual prices, thus leading to the selection for future extrapolation and analysis."

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The extrapolation and analysis are based on Random Forest Regression for CLASS, TYPE, FARE, DESTINATION and ORIGIN. Predicted price behaviors for these can be seen in individual graphs with analysis.\n",
    "<br>From the analysis, we can see that the price variation has significantly less influence over the period of time, compared to other parameters - TYPE, CLASS, FARE, ORIGIN and DESTINATION.\n",
    "<br>Therefore, it can also be concluded that the price variation does not only depend on the period but also several other parameters\n",
    "<br>From the evaluation, we can also see that Random Forest Regression is the most accurate machine learning model to predict the ticket prices.\n",
    "<br>Based on the above predicted price behavior the users are facilitated to opt and plan their travel accordingly."

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### FUTURE OUTLOOK\n",
    "\n",
    "This is a preliminary research focusing on the machine learning models applied on the Spanish Train dataset. We can also conclude that there are several parameters other than the route and period of travel which influence the demand of the tickets. Apart from these, there may be several other parameters which influence the price of the tickets which can be taken as a future research. This analysis is done only for train ticket price prediction for Spanish high-speed trains. The research can be extended to not only train tickets but also flights tickets for all over the world. This study proves the potential of machine learning algorithms and models in the technology domain and the effectiveness of using it for forecasting and prediction."
   ]
